abstract: A selective listing by critics of The Times: New or noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    * BADI ASSAD, Joe's Pub, at the Public Theater, 425 Lafayette Street, at Astor Place, East Village, (212) 539-8778 or (212) 239-6200. Badi Assad, the sister of Sergio and Odair Assad, is a member of a family of remarkable Brazilian guitarists. Unlike her siblings, she sings, too, adding one more level of melody and counterpoint as her fingers fly over her classical guitar. Tonight at 7; admission is $22 (Jon Pareles).

abstract: ATTRACTIONS    Museums and Sites    AMERICAN MUSEUM OF THE MOVING IMAGE, 36-01 35th Avenue, at 36th Street, Astoria, Queens. One of the largest collections of moving-image artifacts. Through Feb. 8, the Fifth New York Film Critics Circle Series, with screenings introduced by various film critics. Tomorrow at 2 p.m., ''Out of the Past'' (1947), directed by Jacques Tourneur, introduced by Andrew Sarris; at 4 p.m. ''The Long Goodbye'' (1973), directed by Robert Altman, introduced by Gene Seymour. Sunday at 2 p.m., ''On the Waterfront'' (1954), directed by Elia Kazan, introduced by Matt Zoller Seitz; at 4:30 p.m. ''In a Lonely Place'' (1950), directed by Nicholas Ray, introduced by Bob Campbell. Other screenings this weekend: tonight at 7:30, '' Musa: The Warrior'' (South Korea/China, 2001), directed by Sun-su Kim; tomorrow and Sunday at 6:30 p.m., ''Children of Paradise'' (''Les Enfants du Paradis'') (France, 1945), directed by Marcel Carn√©. On view through November, ''Tim Burton Drawings,'' an exhibition of more than 24 drawings, watercolors and sketches related to his films. Museum hours: Wednesdays through Thursdays, noon to 5 p.m.; Fridays, noon to 8 p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m.; and by appointment. Film and video showings are free with admission unless otherwise noted. Museum admission: $10; 65+ and students, $7.50; ages 5 to 18, $5; free for members and children 4 and younger and for everyone, Fridays from 4 to 8 p.m.; Friday evenings screenings are extra. Information: (718) 784-0077 or www.movingimage.us.

abstract: A selective listing by critics of The Times: New or noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    AHMED ABDULLAH'S EBONIC TONES, Up Over Jazz Cafe, 351 Flatbush Avenue, near Seventh Avenue, Prospect Heights, Brooklyn, (718) 398-5413. The trumpeter Ahmed Abdullah had a memorable niche in New York's underground jazz scene during the 1980's, as a free-jazz musician intrigued by rhythmic vamps that gave his work a cohesion. (He played briefly with the great drummer Ed Blackwell and with the tenor saxophonist David S. Ware.) This group includes two other noteworthy colleagues from that time and place: the violinist Billy Bang and the bassist Alex Blake. Sets are tonight and tomorrow night at 9, 11, and 12:30; cover charge is $18 and there is a $5 minimum (Ben Ratliff).
